        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our targeted region is largely unexplored in high resolution and sensitive millimeter observations. Although our major goal is to detect dust continuum emission, the proposed observations also play a role of constraining the gas content for the first time, taken the
advantage of the unprecedented sensitivity of ALMA. Therefore, our spectral windows are tuned to cover CO 2-1 and C18O 2-1 lines. In case of the serendipitous detection of other lines (either from our target source, or is confusion from ambient gas), we will use FDM mode at no extra cost of continuum sensitivity. The present correlator tuning will permit robustly picking out the confusion (if exists). If we did detect spectral lines from our source, the proposed velocity
resolution is appropriate for analyzing the line profile to derive gas kinematics.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The main goal of this program is to resolve the debris disk proposed as one of the origins for the circumstellar dust around the Helix WD. Therefore, the required angular resolution and observational depth are designed to reach this goal. Based on our model (simulated image in Figure 2b), the debris belt has radial sizes of 35 to 100 AU. At the Helix distance (219 pc), 0.15" resolution is needed to resolve the structure. The alternative scenario for the circumstellar dust is a scaled-down post-AGB binary disk, which is expected to be compact (not resolved). </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We use SED models fitted to the detailed shape of the disk SED that is composed of measurements from Spitzer, Herschel, SMA and EVLA, to estimate the expected flux density at 1.3 mm and disk surface brightness. For the origin of a post-AGB binary disk, we adopt a face-on opaque ring model from Jura (2003). This opaque ring has a sizes of 0.5-2 AU radially (i.e, an angular size &lt;0.02"). The proposed observation will yield a compact source at the center with S/N &gt;~100 if the disk has a binary origin. For the origin of a debris disk, we use a typical optically-thin debris disk model (e.g, Su et al. 2014), and compute the expected disk surface brightness assuming an axis-symmetric geometry (no density enhancement/clump). This debris disk is expected to have an inner radius of 35-50 AU and an outer radius &lt;100 AU (i.e., angular sizes of 0.3" - 1" in diameter). To minimize the confusion induced by the extended nebula in the antenna sidelobe, the C36-5 configuration at band 6 with a beam of 0.15" is best suited to detect and resolve the debris disk. Based on the ALMA OST simulated image, the debris ring can be detected at &gt;~5.5 sigma across the whole disk circumference. The final observed S/N is most likely to be higher if the disk is inclined and/or has some mixture of amorphous carbon grains. 
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Although our major goal is to detect dust continuum emission, the proposed observations also play a role of constraining the gas content for the first time, taken the advantage of the unprecedented sensitivity of ALMA. Therefore, our spectral windows are tuned to cover CO 2-1 and C18O 2-1 lines. In case of the serendipitous detection of other lines (either from our target source, or is confusion from ambient gas), we will use FDM mode at no extra cost of continuum sensitivity. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_HIGH_DATA_RATE</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
